    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "now that we have Haskell and Julia and  F# kernels (and so on...) it's not actually a safe assumption that that code blocks are going to be python. Indeed, this is one of the selling points for those languages (Julia in particular), that the are able to use all of our conversion machinery for their own purposes out of the box.\n\nI've opened a pull request to fix the reference to backticks, since now we just indent, but you can get backticks in the following manner:\n\nMake a new template file that inherits from `markdown.tpl` and overrides the input block.\n\n``````\n{% extends 'markdown.tpl' %}\n\n{% block input %}\n```python\n{{ cell.input}}\n```\n{% endblock input %}\n``````\n\nIf you call the above file `backticks.tmpl`, then just run\n\n`ipython nbconvert --to=markdown --template=backticks.tpl my_notebook.ipynb`\n"
  },
